{{Infobox Artwork |image_file = Sir Joshua Reynolds 004.jpg |title = Lady Cockburn and Her Three Eldest Sons |artist = [[Joshua Reynolds]] |year = 1773&ndash;1775 |museum = [[National Gallery]] |height_metric = 141.5 |width_metric = 113 |metric_unit = cm |imperial_unit = in |city = [[London]] |medium = [[oil on canvas]] }}
'''''Lady Cockburn and Her Three Eldest Sons''''' (1775) is an [[oil on canvas]] [[portrait]] by [[Joshua Reynolds]]. Work began on the picture in 1773, and, in [[Grand Manner]] fashion, Reynolds exploited two classical paintings: the attitude of the child on the left was modelled on Cupid in [[Velázquez]]'s ''[[Rokeby Venus|Toilet of Venus]]'' whilst the general composition was inspired by [[Anthony van Dyck]]'s ''Charity''. The painting passed to Mister Cockburn's son George, and then to his daughter, Mister Hamilton, the wife of Sir James Hamilton.<ref name=great>[https://books.google.com/books?id=CzQdLzuxWD4C&pg=PA282&dq=%22lady+cockburn%22&as_brr=3&client=firefox-a#PPA285,M1 Great Pictures as Seen and Described by Famous Writers], Esther Singleton, p285, 2007, accessed June 2009</ref> It was bequeathed to London's [[National Gallery, London|National Gallery]] in 1906.<ref name=ng>[http://www.nationalgallery.org.uk/cgi-bin/WebObjects.dll/CollectionPublisher.woa/wa/work?workNumber=ng2077 Lady Cockburn and her Three Eldest Sons], [[National Gallery, London]]</ref> The painting is one of the few signed by Reynolds: Lady Cockburn's dress bears his signature and the year 1775.<ref name=great/>
Lady Cockburn (Augusta Anne Ayscough, 1749–1837) was the daughter of [[Francis Ayscough]]<ref name=burke/> and his wife Anne. She married [[Sir James Cockburn, 8th Baronet|Sir James Cockburn]] ({{IPAc-en|ˈ|k|oʊ|b|ər|n}}, [[Scottish English]]: {{IPA-endia|ˈkobʌɾn|}}) the 8th Baronet and became Lady Cockburn of [[Langton, County Durham|Langton]] in [[Berwick-upon-Tweed|Berwick]] in 1769.<ref name=burke>[https://books.google.com/books?id=Cq8KAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA268&lpg=PA268&dq=ayscough+berwick+augusta&source=bl&ots=fhCYrBUgAE&sig=ANuOia0xH1Pox08WqTn3n6PvQZU&hl=en&ei=py4ySqe-AcOQjAftm5T5CQ&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=1#PPA268,M1 A General and heraldic dictionary of the peerage and baronetage of the British Empire], p268, 1832, accessed June 2009</ref> The marriage was made as the result of a large marriage settlement of twenty thousand pounds which was arranged by her maternal uncle, [[George Lyttelton, 1st Baron Lyttelton|Sir George Lyttlelton]], her widowed mother and her brother George Edward Ayscough. The money was raised on her father's estate and included three houses in London and two farms.<ref>[http://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/a2a/records.aspx?cat=046-ah&cid=-1#-1 Marriage settlement], The National Archives, accessed June 2009</ref>
Lady Cockburn's first three sons are depicted in the portrait. The first son, [[Sir James Cockburn, 9th Baronet|James]] (b. 1771), became the 9th baronet and [[Governor of Bermuda]] (1811–1819), and her second son, [[George Cockburn|George]] (b. 1772) became an [[Admiral of the Fleet]] and the 10th Baronet. Her third son, [[Sir William Cockburn, 11th Baronet|William]] (b. 1773) became the [[Dean of York]], and her fourth son, Alexander (b. 1776), became [[United Kingdom of Great Britain and Ireland|British]] [[Ambassador#Extraordinary postings|envoy extraordinary]] and minister [[plenipotentiary]] to [[Württemberg]] and the [[Columbia District]] whilst her fifth son, [[Francis Cockburn|Francis]], (b. 1776) became a general after being involved in the early history of Canada as a colony and serving in diplomatic positions in the Bahamas and British Honduras.<ref>[http://www.biographi.ca/009004-119.01-e.php?&id_nbr=4357 Cockburn, Sir Francis], Dictionary of Canadian Biography, accessed June 2009]</ref> Lady Cockburn's daughter, Augusta, was wed in 1807.<ref name=burke/>
